{"title_page": "Vetrimaaran", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vettri Maaran\n| image              = Vetrimaaran Pay Homage to Na Muthukumar.jpg\n| caption            = Vetrimaaran in August 2016\n| birth_name         = Vetri Maaran\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1975|9|04}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/why-vetrimaaran-is-the-most-interesting-director-in-tamil-films-today/story-3qScAYREy8mSWPxEhkasBO.html|title=Why Vetrimaaran is the most interesting director in Tamil films today|date=2 November 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiaglitz.com/director-vetrimaran-celeberates-his-birthday-today-tamil-news-141407|title=Happy Birthday Vetrimaran - Tamil Movie News - IndiaGlitz.com|publisher=}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Cuddalore]], Tamil Nadu, India\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| alma mater         =\n| spouse             = Aarthi\n| children           = 2\n| occupation         = [[Film director]], producer, writer\n| yearsactive        = 2007 \u2013 present\n}}\n\n'''Vetrimaaran''' is an Indian [[film director]], screenwriter, and film producer, who works \nthe [[Tamil film industry]]. As of 2016, he has won four [[National Film Awards]] and one [[Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Award]].\n\nVetri Maaran made his directorial debut with the critically acclaimed ''[[Polladhavan (2007 film)|Polladhavan]]'' (2007). His second feature film ''[[Aadukalam]]'' (2011) won six [[National Film Awards]]. He produces films under his production company, [[Grass Root Film Company]]. His movie [[Visaranai|Visaaranai]] (2016) was selected as India's official entry to [[Academy Awards]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://m.thehindu.com/features/cinema/visaranai-is-indias-official-entry-for-oscars-2017-in-foreign-language-film-category/article9136134.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu |title=Visaaranai to take a shot at Oscar nomination | date=2016-09-23}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVetrimaaran's father Dr. V. Chitravel was a [[Veterinary medicine|veterinary scientist]] and his mother Megala Chitravel is a noted novelist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tehelka.com/story_main50.asp?filename=hub250611TheYear.asp |title=India's Independent Weekly News Magazine |publisher=Tehelka |date= |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article2302077.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first=Liza | last=George | title=Journey of the mind | date=2011-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/66197.html |title=Vetrimaaran's Mother To His Rescue! - Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date=2011-04-27 |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref> He was born in [[Cuddalore]]. He then moved to [[Ranipet]], a suburb of [[Vellore]]. He studied up to his tenth grade in [[Ranipet]].\n\n==Career ==\nIn 1999, Vetrimaaran worked as an assistant director for ''Kadhai Neram'' for [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]]  by [[Balu Mahendra]], featuring 52 short stories for 52 episodes. In a team of 4-5 assistant directors, Vetrimaaran read around 50-60 short stories in a week and shortlist a few and present the synopsis to Balu Mahendra, who would select the required storyline. After Kadai Neram, he went on to work with [[Kadhir]] in ''[[Kadhal Virus]]'' for 2 years, whilst also working with Balu Mahendra for ''[[Julie Ganapathy]]'' and then ''[[Adhu Oru Kana Kaalam]]''. At the time, he prepared a script for [[Dhanush]], who has the lead hero of the films he worked in, and Dhanush immediately accepted the offer after hearing the story. The film titled ''Desiya Nedunchalai 47'' was initially launched with [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] as the music director and [[Ekambaram]] as the cinematographer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/27767.html |title=Dhanush\u2019s Desiya Nedunchalai launched |accessdate=2010-01-06}}</ref> After he found trouble finding producers with [[A. M. Rathnam]] and Salem Chandrasekhar leaving the project after initial interest, Dhanush's sister Dr. Vimala Geetha agreed to produce the film, but she also dropped the film. Dhanush's father [[Kasthuri Raja]] finally agreed to produce the film and [[Kirat Bhattal]] was signed as heroine, while [[Harris Jayaraj]] was selected as music director. However, after two days of shoot the film was shelved and Dhanush opted to pursue other films after the surprise success of his ''[[Thiruvilayadal Arambam]]''.<ref name=\"bwd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.videos.behindwoods.com/videos-q1-09/director-interview/Vetrimaaran.html |title=Vetrimaaran - Tamil Cinema Director Interview - Vetrimaaran &#124; Aadukalam &#124; Polladhavan &#124; Dhanush &#124; G V Prakashkumar &#124; Tapasee - Behindwoods.com |publisher=Videos.behindwoods.com |date= |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref> The film's collapse saw Vetrimaaran approach producer Kadiresan and narrated to him the stories he had prepared but the producer did not like ''Desiya Nedunchaalai 47'', but agreed to work on another project titled ''Polladhavan''.\n\nVetrimaaran has since described that he had \"ample time\" for he production works of ''[[Polladhavan (2007 film)|Polladhavan]]'' as \"Dhanush had confidence in him\". Production designer Durai helped him rope in [[G. V. Prakash Kumar]] to score the film's music, while Dhanush also recommended cinematographer Velraj to Vetrimaaran after the pair had worked together in ''[[Parattai Engira Azhagu Sundaram]]''.<ref name=\"bwd\"/> Vetrimaaran chose Kannada language actor [[Kishore (actor)|Kishore]] to make his Tamil film debut after his assistant gave him rave reviews of the actor's performance in the unfinished [[Prashanth (actor)|Prashanth]]-starrer ''Petrol''. The team held test shoots with both [[Kajal Aggarwal]] and [[Poonam Bajwa]] for the film and released the stills to the media, but Vetrimaaran was still unsatisfied and finished two schedules before finalising on [[Ramya|Divya Spandana]]. The director revealed that there was initially an issue with the actress after she got offended by his words and did not come for the shoot for three days, before Durai intervened.<ref name=\"bwd\"/> The film's story was inspired partly by the lost bike of his friend Andrew and the variety of experiences he had tracking down his vehicle. Vetrimaaran revealed that when he wrote the script, he made many changes to suit the visual medium and for Dhanush on his physical attributes while playing an action hero.<ref name=\"bwd\"/> The film opened in November 2007 to rave reviews, with the critic from Sify.com stating that \"Vetri has made his mentor proud, and his style of narration and takings are very similar to the ace director [Balu Mahendra]\", labelling that the film had shades of [[Vittorio De Sica]]'s 1948 Italian film, ''[[Bicycle Thieves]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/polladhavan-review-tamil-14558540.html |title=Movie Review:Polladhavan |publisher=Sify.com |date= |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref> The reviewer from [[The Hindu]] stated that \"at no point does ''Polladhavan'' sag and that writer-director Vetrimaaran has slogged through his screenplay and the result shows.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/cp/2007/11/16/stories/2007111650080300.htm |title=Cinema Plus / Cinema : Never a dull moment |publisher=The Hindu |date=2007-11-16 |accessdate=2012-04-17 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> The film also emerged successful commercially usurping collections of the [[Vijay (actor)|Vijay]]-starrer ''[[Azhagiya Tamil Magan]]'' and the [[Suriya (actor)|Suriya]]-starrer ''[[Vel (film)|Vel]]'' and subsequently went on to win four [[Vijay Awards]] including [[Vijay Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Vetrimaaran.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2008/05/06/stories/2008050650210400.htm |title=Metro Plus Chennai / Events : Awards and accolades all the way |publisher=The Hindu |date=2008-05-06 |accessdate=2012-04-17 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/polladhavan-pick-of-diwali-news-tamil-kkfuuQdcbhb.html |title=Polladhavan - Pick of Diwali! |publisher=Sify.com |date=2007-11-14 |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref>\n\nVetrimaaran is currently undertaking pre-production and scripting work for his next directorial venture, ''Vada Chennai'', a tale on the mafia wars of North Chennai. When announced in 2009, [[Karthi]] was initially touted to play the lead role, although an official announcement from the producers in 2012 revealed that [[Silambarasan]], [[Rana Daggubati]], [[Divya Spandana]] and [[Andrea Jeremiah]] would essay pivotal roles in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/dec-11-03/str-andrea-19-12-11.html |title=Latest On Str - Vetrimaaran Film - Str - Andrea - Tamil Movie News |publisher=Behindwoods.com |date=2011-12-19 |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Dhanush-Vetri-Maaran-to-work-on-Vada-Chennais-sequel-too/articleshow/48413552.cms|title=Dhanush-Vetri Maaran to work on Vada Chennai\u2019s sequel, too|publisher=behindwoods.com|date=10 August 2015}}</ref> The director also revealed that his fourth venture would see him recombine with Dhanush yet again. Vada Chennai released on 18 October 2018. The film opened to largely positive reviews.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2011/02/16/stories/2011021650180400.htm |title=Metro Plus Coimbatore / People : Two stories of success |publisher=The Hindu |date=2011-02-16 |accessdate=2012-04-17 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> In 2012, Vetrimaaran also launched his own production house called the Grass Root Film Company and launched his maiden project, ''Udhayam - NH47'' with [[Siddharth (actor)|Siddharth]] in the lead role and his associate Manimaran as director.\n\nIn 2016, he announced a movie based on the novel 'Shoes Of The Dead' written by [[New Delhi]] based author [[Kota Neelima]] but he is yet to start its shooting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Neelima Kota is confident that Vetrimaaran will do justice to her book|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/shoe-of-the-dead-neelima-kota-is-confident-that-vetrimaaran-will-do-justice-to-her-book/1/624222.html|newspaper=India Today|date=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn Dec 2018, Vetrimaaran-Dhanush announced that they will take a break to shoot ''[[Asuran (2019 film)|Asuran]]'' before commencing Vadachennai part 2. The movie was based on a Tamil novel titled 'Vekkai'.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dhanush-Vetrimaaran's next titled 'Asuran', first look poster out|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/dhanush-vetrimaarans-next-titled-asuran-first-look-poster-out-93966|newspaper=Newsminute|date=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Film\n![[Film director|Director]]\n![[Film producer|Producer]]\n!Notes\n|-\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Polladhavan (2007 film)|Polladhavan]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n|[[Vijay Award for Best Director]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Aadukalam]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Director]]<br>[[National Film Award for Best Screenplay]]<br>[[Filmfare Award for Best Tamil Director]]<br>[[1st South Indian International Movie Awards|SIIMA Award for Best Director]]<br />[[Vijay Award for Best Director]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2013\n| ''[[Udhayam NH4]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Naan Rajavaga Pogiren]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| As dialogue writer\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Poriyaalan]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Kaaka Muttai|Kaakka Muttai]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Children's Film]]<br>[[Filmfare Award for Best Film \u2013 Tamil]]<br>[[Edison Awards (India)|Edison Award for Best Producer]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n| ''[[Visaranai|Visaaranai]]'' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Tamil]]<br>[[Vikatan]] Award for Best Director\n|-\n| ''[[Kodi (film)|Kodi]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2017\n| ''[[Lens (film)|Lens]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2018\n| ''[[Annanukku Jai (2018 film)|Annanukku Jai]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Vada Chennai]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| [[Ananda Vikatan Cinema Awards |Ananda Vikatan Cinema Award for Best Screenplay]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2019\n|''[[Asuran (2019 film)|Asuran]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Miga Miga Avasaram]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2020\n|Ajnabi\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n|\n|-\n|Netflix Anthology \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n|\n|-\n|2021\n|Vadivasal\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above categories/infobox footers by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=nm4274575}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Vetrimaaran}}\n{{NationalFilmAwardBestDirection}}\n{{NationalFilmAwardBestScreenplay}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestTamilDirector}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Tamil film directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Best Director National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Cuddalore district]]\n[[Category:Tamil film producers]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Best Original Screenplay National Film Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vettri Maaran\n| image              = Vetrimaaran Pay Homage to Na Muthukumar.jpg\n| caption            = Vetrimaaran in August 2016\n| birth_name         = Vetri Maaran\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1975|9|04}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/why-vetrimaaran-is-the-most-interesting-director-in-tamil-films-today/story-3qScAYREy8mSWPxEhkasBO.html|title=Why Vetrimaaran is the most interesting director in Tamil films today|date=2 November 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiaglitz.com/director-vetrimaran-celeberates-his-birthday-today-tamil-news-141407|title=Happy Birthday Vetrimaran - Tamil Movie News - IndiaGlitz.com|publisher=}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Cuddalore]], Tamil Nadu, India\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| alma mater         =\n| spouse             = Aarthi\n| children           = 2\n| occupation         = [[Film director]], producer, writer\n| yearsactive        = 2007 \u2013 present\n}}\n\n'''Vetrimaaran''' is an Indian [[film director]], screenwriter, and film producer, who works in the [[Tamil film industry]]. As of 2016, he has won four [[National Film Awards]] and one [[Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Award]].\n\nVetri Maaran made his directorial debut with the critically acclaimed ''[[Polladhavan (2007 film)|Polladhavan]]'' (2007). His second feature film ''[[Aadukalam]]'' (2011) won six [[National Film Awards]]. He produces films under his production company, [[Grass Root Film Company]]. His movie [[Visaranai|Visaaranai]] (2016) was selected as India's official entry to [[Academy Awards]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://m.thehindu.com/features/cinema/visaranai-is-indias-official-entry-for-oscars-2017-in-foreign-language-film-category/article9136134.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu |title=Visaaranai to take a shot at Oscar nomination | date=2016-09-23}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVetrimaaran's father Dr. V. Chitravel was a [[Veterinary medicine|veterinary scientist]] and his mother Megala Chitravel is a noted novelist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tehelka.com/story_main50.asp?filename=hub250611TheYear.asp |title=India's Independent Weekly News Magazine |publisher=Tehelka |date= |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article2302077.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first=Liza | last=George | title=Journey of the mind | date=2011-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/66197.html |title=Vetrimaaran's Mother To His Rescue! - Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date=2011-04-27 |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref> He was born in [[Cuddalore]]. He then moved to [[Ranipet]], a suburb of [[Vellore]]. He studied up to his tenth grade in [[Ranipet]].\n\n==Career ==\nIn 1999, Vetrimaaran worked as an assistant director for ''Kadhai Neram'' for [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]]  by [[Balu Mahendra]], featuring 52 short stories for 52 episodes. In a team of 4-5 assistant directors, Vetrimaaran read around 50-60 short stories in a week and shortlist a few and present the synopsis to Balu Mahendra, who would select the required storyline. After Kadai Neram, he went on to work with [[Kadhir]] in ''[[Kadhal Virus]]'' for 2 years, whilst also working with Balu Mahendra for ''[[Julie Ganapathy]]'' and then ''[[Adhu Oru Kana Kaalam]]''. At the time, he prepared a script for [[Dhanush]], who has the lead hero of the films he worked in, and Dhanush immediately accepted the offer after hearing the story. The film titled ''Desiya Nedunchalai 47'' was initially launched with [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] as the music director and [[Ekambaram]] as the cinematographer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/27767.html |title=Dhanush\u2019s Desiya Nedunchalai launched |accessdate=2010-01-06}}</ref> After he found trouble finding producers with [[A. M. Rathnam]] and Salem Chandrasekhar leaving the project after initial interest, Dhanush's sister Dr. Vimala Geetha agreed to produce the film, but she also dropped the film. Dhanush's father [[Kasthuri Raja]] finally agreed to produce the film and [[Kirat Bhattal]] was signed as heroine, while [[Harris Jayaraj]] was selected as music director. However, after two days of shoot the film was shelved and Dhanush opted to pursue other films after the surprise success of his ''[[Thiruvilayadal Arambam]]''.<ref name=\"bwd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.videos.behindwoods.com/videos-q1-09/director-interview/Vetrimaaran.html |title=Vetrimaaran - Tamil Cinema Director Interview - Vetrimaaran &#124; Aadukalam &#124; Polladhavan &#124; Dhanush &#124; G V Prakashkumar &#124; Tapasee - Behindwoods.com |publisher=Videos.behindwoods.com |date= |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref> The film's collapse saw Vetrimaaran approach producer Kadiresan and narrated to him the stories he had prepared but the producer did not like ''Desiya Nedunchaalai 47'', but agreed to work on another project titled ''Polladhavan''.\n\nVetrimaaran has since described that he had \"ample time\" for he production works of ''[[Polladhavan (2007 film)|Polladhavan]]'' as \"Dhanush had confidence in him\". Production designer Durai helped him rope in [[G. V. Prakash Kumar]] to score the film's music, while Dhanush also recommended cinematographer Velraj to Vetrimaaran after the pair had worked together in ''[[Parattai Engira Azhagu Sundaram]]''.<ref name=\"bwd\"/> Vetrimaaran chose Kannada language actor [[Kishore (actor)|Kishore]] to make his Tamil film debut after his assistant gave him rave reviews of the actor's performance in the unfinished [[Prashanth (actor)|Prashanth]]-starrer ''Petrol''. The team held test shoots with both [[Kajal Aggarwal]] and [[Poonam Bajwa]] for the film and released the stills to the media, but Vetrimaaran was still unsatisfied and finished two schedules before finalising on [[Ramya|Divya Spandana]]. The director revealed that there was initially an issue with the actress after she got offended by his words and did not come for the shoot for three days, before Durai intervened.<ref name=\"bwd\"/> The film's story was inspired partly by the lost bike of his friend Andrew and the variety of experiences he had tracking down his vehicle. Vetrimaaran revealed that when he wrote the script, he made many changes to suit the visual medium and for Dhanush on his physical attributes while playing an action hero.<ref name=\"bwd\"/> The film opened in November 2007 to rave reviews, with the critic from Sify.com stating that \"Vetri has made his mentor proud, and his style of narration and takings are very similar to the ace director [Balu Mahendra]\", labelling that the film had shades of [[Vittorio De Sica]]'s 1948 Italian film, ''[[Bicycle Thieves]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/polladhavan-review-tamil-14558540.html |title=Movie Review:Polladhavan |publisher=Sify.com |date= |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref> The reviewer from [[The Hindu]] stated that \"at no point does ''Polladhavan'' sag and that writer-director Vetrimaaran has slogged through his screenplay and the result shows.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/cp/2007/11/16/stories/2007111650080300.htm |title=Cinema Plus / Cinema : Never a dull moment |publisher=The Hindu |date=2007-11-16 |accessdate=2012-04-17 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> The film also emerged successful commercially usurping collections of the [[Vijay (actor)|Vijay]]-starrer ''[[Azhagiya Tamil Magan]]'' and the [[Suriya (actor)|Suriya]]-starrer ''[[Vel (film)|Vel]]'' and subsequently went on to win four [[Vijay Awards]] including [[Vijay Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Vetrimaaran.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2008/05/06/stories/2008050650210400.htm |title=Metro Plus Chennai / Events : Awards and accolades all the way |publisher=The Hindu |date=2008-05-06 |accessdate=2012-04-17 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/polladhavan-pick-of-diwali-news-tamil-kkfuuQdcbhb.html |title=Polladhavan - Pick of Diwali! |publisher=Sify.com |date=2007-11-14 |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref>\n\nVetrimaaran is currently undertaking pre-production and scripting work for his next directorial venture, ''Vada Chennai'', a tale on the mafia wars of North Chennai. When announced in 2009, [[Karthi]] was initially touted to play the lead role, although an official announcement from the producers in 2012 revealed that [[Silambarasan]], [[Rana Daggubati]], [[Divya Spandana]] and [[Andrea Jeremiah]] would essay pivotal roles in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/dec-11-03/str-andrea-19-12-11.html |title=Latest On Str - Vetrimaaran Film - Str - Andrea - Tamil Movie News |publisher=Behindwoods.com |date=2011-12-19 |accessdate=2012-04-17}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Dhanush-Vetri-Maaran-to-work-on-Vada-Chennais-sequel-too/articleshow/48413552.cms|title=Dhanush-Vetri Maaran to work on Vada Chennai\u2019s sequel, too|publisher=behindwoods.com|date=10 August 2015}}</ref> The director also revealed that his fourth venture would see him recombine with Dhanush yet again. Vada Chennai released on 18 October 2018. The film opened to largely positive reviews.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2011/02/16/stories/2011021650180400.htm |title=Metro Plus Coimbatore / People : Two stories of success |publisher=The Hindu |date=2011-02-16 |accessdate=2012-04-17 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> In 2012, Vetrimaaran also launched his own production house called the Grass Root Film Company and launched his maiden project, ''Udhayam - NH47'' with [[Siddharth (actor)|Siddharth]] in the lead role and his associate Manimaran as director.\n\nIn 2016, he announced a movie based on the novel 'Shoes Of The Dead' written by [[New Delhi]] based author [[Kota Neelima]] but he is yet to start its shooting.<ref>{{cite news|title=Neelima Kota is confident that Vetrimaaran will do justice to her book|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/shoe-of-the-dead-neelima-kota-is-confident-that-vetrimaaran-will-do-justice-to-her-book/1/624222.html|newspaper=India Today|date=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn Dec 2018, Vetrimaaran-Dhanush announced that they will take a break to shoot ''[[Asuran (2019 film)|Asuran]]'' before commencing Vadachennai part 2. The movie was based on a Tamil novel titled 'Vekkai'.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dhanush-Vetrimaaran's next titled 'Asuran', first look poster out|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/dhanush-vetrimaarans-next-titled-asuran-first-look-poster-out-93966|newspaper=Newsminute|date=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Film\n![[Film director|Director]]\n![[Film producer|Producer]]\n!Notes\n|-\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Polladhavan (2007 film)|Polladhavan]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n|[[Vijay Award for Best Director]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Aadukalam]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Director]]<br>[[National Film Award for Best Screenplay]]<br>[[Filmfare Award for Best Tamil Director]]<br>[[1st South Indian International Movie Awards|SIIMA Award for Best Director]]<br />[[Vijay Award for Best Director]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2013\n| ''[[Udhayam NH4]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Naan Rajavaga Pogiren]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| As dialogue writer\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Poriyaalan]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Kaaka Muttai|Kaakka Muttai]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Children's Film]]<br>[[Filmfare Award for Best Film \u2013 Tamil]]<br>[[Edison Awards (India)|Edison Award for Best Producer]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n| ''[[Visaranai|Visaaranai]]'' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Tamil]]<br>[[Vikatan]] Award for Best Director\n|-\n| ''[[Kodi (film)|Kodi]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2017\n| ''[[Lens (film)|Lens]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2018\n| ''[[Annanukku Jai (2018 film)|Annanukku Jai]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Vada Chennai]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| [[Ananda Vikatan Cinema Awards |Ananda Vikatan Cinema Award for Best Screenplay]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2019\n|''[[Asuran (2019 film)|Asuran]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Miga Miga Avasaram]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2020\n|Ajnabi\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n|\n|-\n|Netflix Anthology \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{n}}\n|\n|-\n|2021\n|Vadivasal\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{y}}\n| style=\