{"title_page": "Bhonsle (film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Bhonsle\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Devashish Makhija]]\n| producer       = [[Manoj Bajpayee]]<br>[[Piiyush Singh]]<br>Abhayanand Singh<br>Saurabh Gupta<br>Sandiip Kapoor\n| writer         = Devashish Makhija<br>Mirat Trivedi<br>Sharanya Rajgopal\n| starring       = Manoj Bajpayee<br>Santosh Juvekar\n| music          = Mangesh Dhakde\n| cinematography = Jigmet Wangchuk\n| editing        = [[Shweta Venkat Mathew]]\n| studio         = Muvizz\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2018|10|5|[[Busan International Film Festival|Busan]]|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 132 min\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''Bhonsle''''' is a 2018 Indian [[Hindi]]-language [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] film written and directed by [[Devashish Makhija]]. The film stars [[Manoj Bajpayee]], who is also the co-producer, in the title role of a retired Mumbai cop who befriends a North Indian girl and her brother, when the local politicians are trying to get rid of the migrants. Its first look was launched at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/cannes-film-festival-2018-manoj-bajpayee-returns-to-french-riviera-with-devashish-makhija-political-drama-bhonsle-4466505.html|title=Cannes Film Festival 2018: Manoj Bajpayee returns to French Riviera with Devashish Makhija' political drama Bhonsle|publisher=Firstpost|date=12 May 2018|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> \n\n''Bhonsle'' was premiered in the 'A Window on Asian Cinema' section of the 2018 [[Busan International Film Festival]] and was also screened in the non-competitive India Story section at the [[Mumbai Academy of the Moving Image#Film Festival|MAMI Film Festival]], the 2018 [[Dharamshala International Film Festival]], the 2019 [[International Film Festival Rotterdam]], the [[Bengaluru International Film Festival]] and the Singapore South Asian film festival.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/entertainment/bollywood-manoj-bajpayee-s-bhonsle-to-be-premiered-at-busan-international-film-festival-2018-461424|title=Manoj Bajpayee's Bhonsle to be premiered at Busan International Film Festival 2018|publisher=India TV|date=4 September 2018|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=scroll>{{cite news|url=https://scroll.in/reel/895854/in-bhonsle-manoj-bajpayees-mumbai-constable-has-something-to-say-on-the-insider-outsider-debate|title=In 'Bhonsle', Manoj Bajpayee's Mumbai constable has something to say on the insider-outsider debate|last=Ramnath|first=Nandini|publisher=Scroll.in|date=26 September 2018|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/i-like-proving-people-wrong-manoj-bajpayee/article25444353.ece|title=I like proving people wrong: Manoj Bajpayee|last=Khan|first=Murtaza Ali Khan|work=The Hindu|date=8 November 2018|accessdate=9 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/hindi/2019/jan/26/bhonsles-outing-at-rotterdam-film-fest-1930248.html|title=Bhonsle's outing at Rotterdam film fest|work=The New Indian Express|date=26 January 2019|accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/biffes-2019-chat-debashish-720673.html|title=BIFFes 2019: Chat with Debashish Makhija of 'Bhonsle'|work=Deccan Herald|date=27 February 2019|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spotboye.com/marathi/marathi-news/bhonsle-santosh-juvekar-s-film-is-officially-selected-for-3rd-singapore-south-asian-international-film-festival-2019/5d656c9709da697670cc8d50|title=Selected For 3rd Singapore South Asian International Film Festival 2019|website=SpotboyE|date=27 August 2019|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> It won the Best Screenplay and Best Director Award at the Asian Film Festival Barcelona.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/manoj-bajpayees-bhonsle-wins-big-at-barcelona-fest/1663253|title=Manoj Bajpayee''s ''Bhonsle'' wins big at Barcelona fest|work=Outlook|date=15 November 2019|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Manoj Bajpayee]] as Ganpath Bhonsle\n*[[Santosh Juvekar]] as Vilas\n*[[Ipshita Chakraborty Singh]]\n*Virat Vaibhav as Lalu\n*Neetu Pande\n\n==Production==\nMakhija started writing the script of ''Bhonsle'' in 2011 and completed it in 2015 but could not find the producers. In 2016, Makhija directed an 11-minute short film titled ''Taandav'' starring [[Manoj Bajpayee]], about a head constable who breaks out into a dance to deal with the strains of his life.<ref name=scroll/> Bajpayee had suggested him to make a short \"to prove that they could carry off the idea.\"<ref name=scroll/> Makhija said that he made the short because he was not able to make ''Bhonsle''. He said that the purpose of the short was to \"show the world that a film about a havaldar (constable) could be interesting.\"<ref name=scroll/> Makhija took inspiration for Bhonsale's mannerisms from his father who had become \"something else\" after Makhija left for [[Mumbai]] from his hometown [[Kolkata]].<ref name=scroll/> The script was selected by the [[National Film Development Corporation of India]] for their event, Film Bazaar in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/muvizz-coms-bhonsle-starring-manoj-bajpayee-selected-by-nfdc-for-film-bazaar/articleshow/55353906.cms|title=Muvizz.com's 'Bhonsle' starring Manoj Bajpayee selected by NFDC for Film Bazaar|last=Laghate|first=Gaurav|work=The Economic Times|date=10 November 2016|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe film's principal photography began on 21 October 2017. The Ganpati festival scene was shot for two days in Mumbai in August that forms a backdrop in the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/festivals/busan-helmer-devashish-makhija-set-for-bhonsle-exclusive-1202589024/|title=Busan: Helmer Devashish Makhija set for \"Bhonsle\" (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Ramachandran|first=Naman|work=Variety|date=13 October 2017|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> For the pullout shot on the day of the Ganpati immersion, Bajpayee was placed in the crowd of 70,000 people. The scene took six retakes to complete and throughout the shoot no one recognised Bajpayee.<ref name=scroll/> The filming was completed in late December, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/manoj-bajpayee-wraps-up-devashish-makhija-s-bhonsle-in-mumbai/story-rFziSCP0ovZK8fpl9cInEP.html|title=Manoj Bajpayee wraps up Devashish Makhija's Bhonsle in Mumbai|work=Hindustan Times|date=29 December 2017|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> Several scenes were shot in closed narrow spaces as Makhija wanted to \"create a sense of suffocation.\"<ref name=scroll/>\n\n==Reception==\nDeborah Young of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' praised Bajpayee's performance in the film and said that his \"hermit retiree emerges as a quiet-spoken hero who opposes the racist hate-mongering around him with cool disdain.\" She felt that the film \"builds tension well as it goes along\", but called its first half \"punishing\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/bhonsle-1155739|title='Bhonsle': Film Review: Mumbai 2018|last=Young|first=Deborah|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=28 October 2018|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> Anupam Kant Verma of [[Firstpost]] wrote: \"To Makhija\u2019s peculiar blend of technical proficiency and poetic beats, Bajpayee brings the gravitas and masterful restraint that tugs at the kite of the director\u2019s imagination the moment it threatens to pull away, in effect, harmonising the film experience.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bhonsle-movie-review-devashish-makhijas-fascinating-character-study-is-enriched-by-manoj-bajpayees-performance-5505521.html|title=Bhonsle movie review: Devashish Makhija's fascinating character study is enriched by Manoj Bajpayee's performance|last=Verma|first=Anupam Kant|publisher=Firstpost|date=5 November 2018|accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref> J. Hurtado of [[Screen Anarchy]] wrote: \"It's an exceptional film bolstered by a nearly silent performance from Manoj Bajpayee, one of India's finest actors, who also stepped in to produce the film when things were looking dire during production.\" He also included it in his list of 14 Favorite Indian Films of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenanarchy.com/2019/01/j-hurtados-13-favorite-indian-films-of-2018-gallery.html|title=J Hurtado's 14 Favorite Indian Films of 2018|last=Hurtado|first=J|publisher=Screen Anarchy|date=3 January 2018|accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|tt8476998}}\n\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Films set in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement in fiction]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Bhonsle\n| image          =\n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Devashish Makhija]]\n| producer       = [[Manoj Bajpayee]]<br>Piiyush Singh<br>Abhayanand Singh<br>Saurabh Gupta<br>Sandiip Kapoor\n| writer         = Devashish Makhija<br>Mirat Trivedi<br>Sharanya Rajgopal\n| starring       = Manoj Bajpayee<br>Santosh Juvekar\n| music          = Mangesh Dhakde\n| cinematography = Jigmet Wangchuk\n| editing        = [[Shweta Venkat Mathew]]\n| studio         = Muvizz\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2018|10|5|[[Busan International Film Festival|Busan]]|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 132 min\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n'''''Bhonsle''''' is a 2018 Indian [[Hindi]]-language [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] film written and directed by [[Devashish Makhija]]. The film stars [[Manoj Bajpayee]], who is also the co-producer, in the title role of a retired Mumbai cop who befriends a North Indian girl and her brother, when the local politicians are trying to get rid of the migrants. Its first look was launched at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/cannes-film-festival-2018-manoj-bajpayee-returns-to-french-riviera-with-devashish-makhija-political-drama-bhonsle-4466505.html|title=Cannes Film Festival 2018: Manoj Bajpayee returns to French Riviera with Devashish Makhija' political drama Bhonsle|publisher=Firstpost|date=12 May 2018|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> \n\n''Bhonsle'' was premiered in the 'A Window on Asian Cinema' section of the 2018 [[Busan International Film Festival]] and was also screened in the non-competitive India Story section at the [[Mumbai Academy of the Moving Image#Film Festival|MAMI Film Festival]], the 2018 [[Dharamshala International Film Festival]], the 2019 [[International Film Festival Rotterdam]], the [[Bengaluru International Film Festival]] and the Singapore South Asian film festival.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/entertainment/bollywood-manoj-bajpayee-s-bhonsle-to-be-premiered-at-busan-international-film-festival-2018-461424|title=Manoj Bajpayee's Bhonsle to be premiered at Busan International Film Festival 2018|publisher=India TV|date=4 September 2018|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=scroll>{{cite news|url=https://scroll.in/reel/895854/in-bhonsle-manoj-bajpayees-mumbai-constable-has-something-to-say-on-the-insider-outsider-debate|title=In 'Bhonsle', Manoj Bajpayee's Mumbai constable has something to say on the insider-outsider debate|last=Ramnath|first=Nandini|publisher=Scroll.in|date=26 September 2018|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/i-like-proving-people-wrong-manoj-bajpayee/article25444353.ece|title=I like proving people wrong: Manoj Bajpayee|last=Khan|first=Murtaza Ali Khan|work=The Hindu|date=8 November 2018|accessdate=9 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/hindi/2019/jan/26/bhonsles-outing-at-rotterdam-film-fest-1930248.html|title=Bhonsle's outing at Rotterdam film fest|work=The New Indian Express|date=26 January 2019|accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/biffes-2019-chat-debashish-720673.html|title=BIFFes 2019: Chat with Debashish Makhija of 'Bhonsle'|work=Deccan Herald|date=27 February 2019|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spotboye.com/marathi/marathi-news/bhonsle-santosh-juvekar-s-film-is-officially-selected-for-3rd-singapore-south-asian-international-film-festival-2019/5d656c9709da697670cc8d50|title=Selected For 3rd Singapore South Asian International Film Festival 2019|website=SpotboyE|date=27 August 2019|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> It won the Best Screenplay and Best Director Award at the Asian Film Festival Barcelona.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/manoj-bajpayees-bhonsle-wins-big-at-barcelona-fest/1663253|title=Manoj Bajpayee''s ''Bhonsle'' wins big at Barcelona fest|work=Outlook|date=15 November 2019|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Manoj Bajpayee]] as Ganpath Bhonsle\n*[[Santosh Juvekar]] as Vilas\n*[[Ipshita Chakraborty Singh]]\n*Virat Vaibhav as Lalu\n*Neetu Pande\n\n==Production==\nMakhija started writing the script of ''Bhonsle'' in 2011 and completed it in 2015 but could not find the producers. In 2016, Makhija directed an 11-minute short film titled ''Taandav'' starring [[Manoj Bajpayee]], about a head constable who breaks out into a dance to deal with the strains of his life.<ref name=scroll/> Bajpayee had suggested him to make a short \"to prove that they could carry off the idea.\"<ref name=scroll/> Makhija said that he made the short because he was not able to make ''Bhonsle''. He said that the purpose of the short was to \"show the world that a film about a havaldar (constable) could be interesting.\"<ref name=scroll/> Makhija took inspiration for Bhonsale's mannerisms from his father who had become \"something else\" after Makhija left for [[Mumbai]] from his hometown [[Kolkata]].<ref name=scroll/> The script was selected by the [[National Film Development Corporation of India]] for their event, Film Bazaar in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/muvizz-coms-bhonsle-starring-manoj-bajpayee-selected-by-nfdc-for-film-bazaar/articleshow/55353906.cms|title=Muvizz.com's 'Bhonsle' starring Manoj Bajpayee selected by NFDC for Film Bazaar|last=Laghate|first=Gaurav|work=The Economic Times|date=10 November 2016|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe film's principal photography began on 21 October 2017. The Ganpati festival scene was shot for two days in Mumbai in August that forms a backdrop in the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/festivals/busan-helmer-devashish-makhija-set-for-bhonsle-exclusive-1202589024/|title=Busan: Helmer Devashish Makhija set for \"Bhonsle\" (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Ramachandran|first=Naman|work=Variety|date=13 October 2017|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> For the pullout shot on the day of the Ganpati immersion, Bajpayee was placed in the crowd of 70,000 people. The scene took six retakes to complete and throughout the shoot no one recognised Bajpayee.<ref name=scroll/> The filming was completed in late December, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/manoj-bajpayee-wraps-up-devashish-makhija-s-bhonsle-in-mumbai/story-rFziSCP0ovZK8fpl9cInEP.html|title=Manoj Bajpayee wraps up Devashish Makhija's Bhonsle in Mumbai|work=Hindustan Times|date=29 December 2017|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> Several scenes were shot in closed narrow spaces as Makhija wanted to \"create a sense of suffocation.\"<ref name=scroll/>\n\n==Reception==\nDeborah Young of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' praised Bajpayee's performance in the film and said that his \"hermit retiree emerges as a quiet-spoken hero who opposes the racist hate-mongering around him with cool disdain.\" She felt that the film \"builds tension well as it goes along\", but called its first half \"punishing\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/bhonsle-1155739|title='Bhonsle': Film Review: Mumbai 2018|last=Young|first=Deborah|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=28 October 2018|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> Anupam Kant Verma of [[Firstpost]] wrote: \"To Makhija\u2019s peculiar blend of technical proficiency and poetic beats, Bajpayee brings the gravitas and masterful restraint that tugs at the kite of the director\u2019s imagination the moment it threatens to pull away, in effect, harmonising the film experience.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bhonsle-movie-review-devashish-makhijas-fascinating-character-study-is-enriched-by-manoj-bajpayees-performance-5505521.html|title=Bhonsle movie review: Devashish Makhija's fascinating character study is enriched by Manoj Bajpayee's performance|last=Verma|first=Anupam Kant|publisher=Firstpost|date=5 November 2018|accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref> J. Hurtado of [[Screen Anarchy]] wrote: \"It's an exceptional film bolstered by a nearly silent performance from Manoj Bajpayee, one of India's finest actors, who also stepped in to produce the film when things were looking dire during production.\" He also included it in his list of 14 Favorite Indian Films of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenanarchy.com/2019/01/j-hurtados-13-favorite-indian-films-of-2018-gallery.html|title=J Hurtado's 14 Favorite Indian Films of 2018|last=Hurtado|first=J|publisher=Screen Anarchy|date=3 January 2018|accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|tt8476998}}\n\n[[Category:Films shot in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Films set in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement in fiction]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n", "name_user": "Globaldominator", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhonsle_(film)"}
{"title_page": "William Giles (colonial manager)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n[[File:William Giles B7334 15.jpg|thumb|William Giles, c. 1840]]\n'''William Giles''' (27 December 1791 \u2013 11 May 1862), occasionally referred to as William Giles, sen. to distinguish him from his eldest son,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207068115 |title=Mount Barker Election |newspaper=[[Adelaide Times]] |volume=II |issue=417 |location=South Australia |date=29 March 1851 |accessdate=4 April 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> was the third colonial manager of the [[South Australian Company]], and a  South Australian  politician, who was prominent in the founding of the colony of [[South Australia]].\n\n==Early life==\nGiles was born in [[Great Staughton]], [[Huntingdonshire]], England, and was educated at [[Kimbolton School]].<ref name=adb/>\n\n==Travel to South Australia==\nAn apparently close friend of one of the founders of the [[South Australian Company]], [[George Fife Angas]], Giles travelled to South Australia on the ship ''Hartley'' in 1837 accompanied by his new (and pregnant) wife, Emily Elizabeth (n\u00e9e McGeorge) (c. 1814 \u2013 5 August 1876)<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article43012425 Deaths \u2013 Emily Elizabeth Giles] ''South Australian Register'' 7 August 1876 p.4 accessed 2 May 2011</ref> and their 1-year-old daughter Emily jnr.\n \nThe ''Hartley'' was a three-masted vessel measuring 27.13 x 7.19 x 5.61 metres built at [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] in England in 1836. Her owner and captain was Thomas Fewson.<ref name=hartley>[http://www.samemory.sa.gov.au/site/page.cfm?u=61&c=5146 Passenger list of the ''Hartley''] SA Memory</ref> Emily gave birth to her second child, George Hartley Giles during the voyage. William's new family (Emily, Emily jnr and George) was also accompanied by William's nine children from his earlier marriage to Sarah (n\u00e9e Roper).<ref name=detail>[http://www.samemory.sa.gov.au/site/page.cfm?c=4806&mode=singleImage Passenger list of the ''Hartley'' \u2013 detail], SA Memory. The Giles' family are passengers 1 to 12, with the annotation \"George Hartley Giles born at sea\".</ref> On 16 October 1837 the ''Hartley'' arrived at [[Kingscote, South Australia|Kingscote, Kangaroo Island]] where the Company's first settlement was founded.<ref name=Heaton>Heaton, J. Henniker ''Australian Dictionary of Dates and Men of the Time'' George Robertson, Sydney 1879</ref> Once in South Australia, William and Emily had a further ten children.\n\n==Family==\nWilliam married twice: to Sarah Roper (died 1833) on 1 November 1813, and to Emily McGeorge (c.1814 \u2013 5 August 1876) on 12 January 1835. In total he had 21 children and 78 grandchildren.<ref name=adb>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography |last= Tregenza |first= John |year= 1966 |id= A010409b |title=  Giles, William (1791\u20131862) |accessdate= 24 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=detail/>\n\n;Children with Sarah Roper\n* William Giles, (c. 1814 \u2013 14 January 1875)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article40092316 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=16 January 1875 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia |quote=Deaths. At his residence (in) Hackney, William Giles, aged 60.}}</ref> married Margaret McFarlane (11 June 1821 \u2013 22 October 1901), daughter of [[Allan McFarlane]];<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4913146 |title=The Late Mrs. W. Giles |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=23 October 1901 |accessdate=1 February 2013 |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> home at [[Hackney, South Australia|Hackney]] then George Street, [[Norwood, South Australia|Norwood]]. He later had a business in [[Kanmantoo, South Australia|Kanmantoo]] and was not involved in public affairs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article40082736 |title=The Late Mr. Wm. Giles |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XL |issue=8789 |location=South Australia |date=15 January 1875 |accessdate=4 April 2018 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Their son Alan McFarlane Giles ( \u2013 24 November 1888), stationmaster at Tennant Creek, was the sole survivor of a relief party sent to Attack Creek in 1883, saved by an [[Australian aborigine|aboriginal]] woman, and died of [[brain fever]] at [[Renner Springs]] five years later, following a murder to which he was a close witness.\n* Henry Giles (1816 \u2013 10 February 1888)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article46862625 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=13 February 1888 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia |quote=Deaths. At Braemar, Stirling West, Henry Giles, aged 72.}}</ref> married Jane Leslie (1825 \u2013 13 November 1892) in Scotland in 1845;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48558893 |title=Death of an Old Colonist |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=14 November 1892 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> home \"Braemar\", [[Aldgate, South Australia|Stirling West]]. Co-founded stock and station firm Giles & Smith.<ref name=clement/> Their eldest daughter, Amy, married [[John Fullerton Cleland#Family|George Fullerton Cleland]] in 1878.<ref>Lindsay Cleland, [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/cleland-george-fullerton-3232/text4873 'Cleland, George Fullerton (1852\u20131931)'], ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', National Centre of Biography, Australian National University, accessed 29 January 2013</ref>\n* Mary Giles (c. 1818 \u2013 19 September 1893)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article53623019 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=22 September 1893 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia |quote=Deaths. Mary, beloved wife of Josiah Partridge, of Malvern, near Clarendon, SA, aged 75. }}</ref> married Josiah Partridge (1805 \u2013 27 November 1897)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54518502 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=7 December 1897 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> on 22 June 1840;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27441558 |title=Markets |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=27 June 1840 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> home \"Malvern\", near [[Clarendon, South Australia|Clarendon]].\n* [[Thomas Giles (pastoralist)|Thomas \"Tom\" Giles]] (1820 \u2013 12 February 1899)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54410620 |title=The Late Mr. T. Giles |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=21 February 1899 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  married Mary O'Halloran (died c. 1 October 1915) on 20 January 1859. He developed pastoral leases on the Eyre and Yorke Peninsulas.\n:*Dr. W(illiam) Anstey Giles (c. 1860 \u2013 7 May 1944)<!--married Ruth (died 9 September 1907)-->\n:*T. O'Halloran Giles (1863 \u2013 ) married Jean Balfour St. Clair Barr Smith (20 December 1864 \u2013 ) on 4 October 1888. She was a daughter of [[Robert Barr Smith]].\n::*Hew O'Halloran Giles ( \u2013 ) married Nellie Cosford Verco (1901\u20131965), eldest daughter of Dr. W. A. Verco, and great-granddaughter of [[James Crabb Verco]], on 27 October 1920\n:::*[[Geoffrey O'Halloran Giles]] MLC, MHR (27 June 1923 \u2013 18 December 1990)\n::*Robert O'Halloran Giles (c. 1896 \u2013 9 April 1918) was killed in action in Italy.\n:*Dr. Henry O'Halloran Giles (c. 1867 \u2013 9 March 1911)\n:*Eustace Giles (1866 \u2013 24 December 1927), solicitor of Yarra House, Anderson-street, South Yarra, Victoria, died in London\n* James Giles (c. 1821 \u2013 20 December 1861)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article881234 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The South Australian Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=23 December 1861 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> married Eliza Dean (c. 1823 \u2013 5 April 1882) in 1848\n* Jane Isabella \"Minnie\" Giles (1824 \u2013 c. 19 August 1894)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article53648022 |title=Funeral of Mrs. Alfred Watts |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=22 August 1894 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}} This reference includes a useful list of mourners.</ref> married Alfred Watts (c. 1815 \u2013 28 November 1884)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article43803917 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=3 December 1884 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> on 18 May 1842<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article36248709 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[Launceston Examiner]] |location=Tas. |date=4 June 1842 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=5 Edition: Evening |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> They were the original owners of [[Leabrook, South Australia|Leabrook]].<ref>http://www.slsa.sa.gov.au/manning/pn/l/l2.htm Manning Index of South Australia \u2013 Placenames</ref> Watts was a fellow passenger on the ''Hartley'' with Giles and his family, as was Rev. [[T. Q. Stow]], who performed the service. \n* John Stokes Giles (1825\u2013)<ref name=detail/>\n* Lydia Giles (1827 \u2013 25 January 1910)<ref>{{cite news |title=Second Edition |url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=HC19100315.2.20 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |newspaper=Horowhenua Chronicle |date=15 March 1910 |page=3}}</ref> married [[George Waterhouse (politician)|George Waterhouse]] (6 April 1824 \u2013 6 August 1906) on 5 July 1848.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48729267 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=8 July 1848 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Waterhouse was Premier of South Australia from 1861 to 1863 and Premier of New Zealand from 1872 to 1873.\n:*One of their two adopted daughters married [[William Fitzherbert (mayor)|William Fitzherbert]] (1842 \u2013 2 February 1906) in 1876\n* Samuel (1830\u2013 )<ref name=detail/>\n* Sarah (1833\u2013 )\n\n;Children with Emily McGeorge\n* Emily Rebecca Giles (1836 \u2013 24 January 1929)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article35321699 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=25 January 1929 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=12 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> married [[Francis William Stokes]] (1832 \u2013 2 August 1889)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3499537 |title=Cable Messages |newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]] |date=5 August 1889 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> on 17 April 1861<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article50017602 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=20 April 1861 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> developed Konetta (Coonatto ?) Station.\n* George Hartley Giles (c. 1837 \u2013 ) was born on ship ''Hartley'' at sea;<ref name=detail/> practised law, admitted to Supreme Court in 1862,<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article40467328 Accessions to the Bar], SA Register, 24 March 1862, p.2</ref> but was struck off the rolls for misappropriation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41018297 |title=Law and Criminal Courts. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=13 December 1865 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He moved to Queensland, where he ran foul of the law several times. Later references are elusive \u2013 perhaps like [[Charles Whitmore Babbage]], the family used its considerable influence to help him start over in another place, perhaps under another name.\n* Edward Hollingworth Giles (1838 \u2013 18 July 1839)\n* Percy Ludlow Giles (1839 \u2013 20 December 1840)\n* Leonard Hollway Giles (18 May 1841 \u2013 15 January 1898)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article87771096 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The Chronicle (Adelaide)|The Chronicle]] |location=Adelaide |date=22 January 1898 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=9 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> married Marianne <!--not Marrianne, Marion--> Baily (13 February 1854 \u2013 5 May 1901)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article56083783 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=11 May 1901 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> on 12 September 1878<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42995531 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=19 September 1878 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* Hubert Giles (21 October 1842 \u2013 11 August 1901<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4851397 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=12 August 1901 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>), prizewinning student at Adelaide Educational Institution, married Charlotte Julian Kingston (11 September 1845 \u2013 20 May 1913), youngest daughter of Sir [[George Strickland Kingston]] on 17 March 1880.\n* [[Clement Giles]] (1844 \u2013 28 July 1926),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54861976 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=28 July 1926 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=10 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> pastoralist, merchant and politician. A prizewinning student at [[Adelaide Educational Institution]], he became Secretary-manager and first London representative of the South Australian Farmers' Co-operative Union, and later, sole elected representative of Australian farmers on the compulsory wheat pool of 1917.<ref name=adb/><ref name=clement>Carl Bridge (1983) [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/giles-clement-6380 Giles, Clement (1844\u20131926)], ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Vol 9</ref> He married Isabel Cockburn (sister of [[John Cockburn (Australian politician)|Sir John Cockburn]]) on 7 August 1872<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39267743 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=9 August 1872 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* Louis Henry Lobeck Giles (14 July 1845 \u2013 21 November 1902) married Alice Margaret \"Alison\" Andrews (9 February 1862 \u2013 ), second daughter of [[William Buckton Andrews|Rev. Canon Andrews]], on 26 November 1884. He was a prizewinning student at [[Adelaide Educational Institution]] then a licensed land broker at the [[Grange, South Australia|Grange]] and Adelaide.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4900017 |title=Personal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=22 November 1902 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* Acland Giles (c. January 1847 \u2013 8 June 1858)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49777035 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=9 June 1858 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}This reference reckons him the twelfth son.</ref> A student at Adelaide Educational Institution, he won prizes in 1856 and 1857, the second posthumously.\n* Mortimer Giles (1848 \u2013 17 May 1914)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article6416614 |title=Personal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=18 May 1914 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=14 |publisher=National Library of Australia}} A comprehensive obituary.</ref> married Agnes Reid Andrews (c. 1849 \u2013 18 July 1907), the daughter of [[Richard Bullock Andrews|Mr. Justice Andrews]], on 16 May 1874.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39821841 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=19 May 1874 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}} An instance of brothers marrying cousins.</ref> He was a prizewinning student at J. L. Young's [[Adelaide Educational Institution]]. In 1904 he was appointed Registrar-General of Deeds, Registrar of Building Societies, Commissioner of Trade Marks, and Registrar of Copyrights.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4983283 |title=The Civil Service |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=30 June 1904 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n:*Mortimer Giles (1887\u20131979) was admitted to the Bar in 1912.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59233322 |title=Admitted to the Bar |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=22 July 1912 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* Caroline Ada Giles (28 February 1850 \u2013 21 May 1933)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41487200 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=23 May 1933 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> married Charles Edward Stokes (1851\u20131911) on 12 June 1877.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article33749718 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The South Australian Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=13 June 1877 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> She had some success as an artist.<ref>[http://www.daao.org.au/bio/caroline-giles/#artist_biography Biography \u2013 Caroline Giles] ''Design & Art Australia Online'' www.daao.org.au</ref>\n* Florence Giles (13 January 1852 \u2013 30 January 1930)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54160183 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The Register News-Pictorial]] |location=Adelaide |date=31 January 1930 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> married Rev. Francis Herbert Stokes (29 December 1854 \u2013 21 February 1929)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article87455057 |title=Obituary. |newspaper=[[The Chronicle (Adelaide)|The Chronicle]] |location=Adelaide |date=2 March 1929 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=47 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> on 3 September 1879<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article29374537 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The South Australian Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=4 September 1879 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n:*Francis Herbert Stokes, jr. (c. 1890 \u2013 27 April 1915) was killed at [[Gallipoli]] in 1915.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59602439 |title=PTE. F. H. Stokes |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|The Register (Adelaide, SA : 1901 - 1929)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=22 June 1915 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n;Summary\n<center>\n{| class=wikitable\n!   ||         || born ||boy||girl|| died || Age at death\n|-\n| 1 || William || 1814 || 1 ||    || 1875 || 61\n|-\n| 2 || Henry   || 1816 || 2 ||    || 1888 || 72\n|-\n| 3 || Mary    || 1818 ||   || 1  || 1893 || 75\n|-\n| 4 || Thomas  || 1820 || 3 ||    || 1899 || 79\n|-\n| 5 || James   || 1821 || 4 ||    || 1861 || 40\n|-\n| 6 || Jane    || 1824 ||   || 2  || 1894 || 70\n|-\n| 7 || John    || 1825 || 5 ||    ||  ?   ||  \n|-\n| 8 || Lydia   || 1827 ||   || 3  || 1910 || 83\n|-\n| 9 || Samuel  || 1830 || 6 ||    ||  ?   ||  \n|-\n|   || Sarah   || 1833 ||   ||    ||  ?   || Died at birth?\n|- align=center\n|colspan=7| Mrs Sarah Giles died 1833\n|-\n|10 || Emily   || 1836 ||   || 4 || 1929 || 93\n|-\n|11 || George  || 1837 || 7 ||   ||  ?   ||\n|-\n|12 || Edward  || 1838 || 8 ||   || 1839 || 1\n|-\n|13 || Percy   || 1839 || 9 ||   || 1840 || 1\n|-\n|14 || Leonard || 1841 ||10 ||   || 1898 || 57 \n|-\n|15 || Hubert  || 1842 ||11 ||   || 1901 || 59\n|-\n|16 || Clement || 1844 ||12 ||   || 1926 || 82\n|-\n|17 || Louis   || 1845 ||13 ||   || 1902 || 57\n|-\n|18 || Acland  || 1847 ||14 ||   || 1858 || 11 \n|-\n|19 || Mortimer|| 1848 ||15 ||   || 1914 || 66    \n|-\n|20 || Caroline|| 1850 ||   || 5 || 1933 || 83 \n|-\n|21 || Florence|| 1852 ||   || 6 || 1930 || 78   \n|}\n</center>\n\n==Business life==\nShortly after arrival on Kangaroo Island, Giles, [[Thomas Hudson Beare (pioneer)|T. H. Beare]], and [[Henry Mildred]] imported a batch of [[Merino]] ewes from [[Tasmania|Van Diemens Land]] to [[Kangaroo Island]], some of the first brought into the colony, though stock losses on the unusually long trip aboard the ''Cygnet'' were considerable.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article160093755 |title=The Merino in South Australia |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |volume=XLI |issue=2213 |location=South Australia |date=1 March 1884 |accessdate=13 January 2017 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nGiles was appointed Stipendiary Magistrate by [[John Hindmarsh|Governor Hindmarsh]] in 1838<ref name=Heaton/> then appointed as the third colonial manager of the [[South Australian Company]] in January 1841, succeeding [[David McLaren (Colonial Manager)|David McLaren]].<ref name=adb/> He continued as manager until 1861, when he retired.\n\n==Political life==\nGiles stood for the [[Electoral district of Port Adelaide]] in the [[South Australian Legislative Council|first elected parliament]] in July 1851, but was narrowly defeated by [[George Hall (Australian politician)|Captain George Hall]].<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39184005/3952567 Death of the Hon. George Hall, MLC] ''South Australian Register'' 29 January 1867 p.3 accessed 26 June 2011</ref><!--can he have both been beaten at Port Adelaide and won Yatala in 1851?-->\nHe was elected as member for the District of Yatala for five sessions of the [[South Australian Legislative Council]], from July 1851 until 1854.<ref>[http://www.parliament.sa.gov.au/AboutParliament/From1836/Documents/StatisticalRecordoftheLegislature1836to20093.pdf Statistical Record of the Legislature 1836\u20132007] ''Parliament of South Australia'' parliament.sa.gov.au. Tabled 24 April 2007, accessed 16 September 2011.</ref> He was a devout [[Congregationalist]]. As a legislator he opposed state aid to religion,<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/earlyhistorysou00blacgoog |title=The Early History of South Australia: A Romantic Experiment in Colonization |author=John Blacket |year=1907 |publisher=Methodist Book Depot}}</ref> as did his close friend, Rev. [[Thomas Stow|T. Q. Stow]].<ref name=Heaton/>\n\nHe died at his home in [[Beaumont, South Australia|Beaumont]] on 11 May 1862.<ref name=adb/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Giles, William}}\n[[Category:1791 births]]\n[[Category:1862 deaths]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Great Staughton]]\n[[Category:Settlers of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the South Australian Legislative Council]]\n[[Category:People educated at Kimbolton School]]\n[[Category:South Australian Company Colonial Managers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:South Australian families]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n[[File:William Giles B7334 15.jpg|thumb|William Giles, c. 1840]]\n'''William Giles''' (27 December 1791 \u2013 11 May 1862), occasionally referred to as William Giles, sen. to distinguish him from his eldest son,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207068115 |title=Mount Barker Election |newspaper=[[Adelaide Times]] |volume=II |issue=417 |location=South Australia |date=29 March 1851 |accessdate=4 April 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> was the third colonial manager of the [[South Australian Company]], and a  South Australian  politician, who was prominent in the founding of the colony of [[South Australia]].\n\n==Early life==\nGiles was born in [[Great Staughton]], [[Huntingdonshire]], England, and was educated at [[Kimbolton School]].<ref name=adb/>\n\n==Travel to South Australia==\nAn apparently close friend of one of the founders of the [[South Australian Company]], [[George Fife Angas]], Giles travelled to South Australia on the ship ''Hartley'' in 1837 accompanied by his new (and pregnant) wife, Emily Elizabeth (n\u00e9e McGeorge) (c. 1814 \u2013 5 August 1876)<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article43012425 Deaths \u2013 Emily Elizabeth Giles] ''South Australian Register'' 7 August 1876 p.4 accessed 2 May 2011</ref> and their 1-year-old daughter Emily jnr.\n \nThe ''Hartley'' was a three-masted vessel measuring 27.13 x 7.19 x 5.61 metres built at [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] in England in 1836. Her owner and captain was Thomas Fewson.<ref name=hartley>[http://www.samemory.sa.gov.au/site/page.cfm?u=61&c=5146 Passenger list of the ''Hartley''] SA Memory</ref> Emily gave birth to her second child, George Hartley Giles during the voyage. William's new family (Emily, Emily jnr and George) was also accompanied by William's nine children from his earlier marriage to Sarah (n\u00e9e Roper).<ref name=detail>[http://www.samemory.sa.gov.au/site/page.cfm?c=4806&mode=singleImage Passenger list of the ''Hartley'' \u2013 detail], SA Memory. The Giles' family are passengers 1 to 12, with the annotation \"George Hartley Giles born at sea\".</ref> On 16 October 1837 the ''Hartley'' arrived at [[Kingscote, South Australia|Kingscote, Kangaroo Island]] where the Company's first settlement was founded.<ref name=Heaton>Heaton, J. Henniker ''Australian Dictionary of Dates and Men of the Time'' George Robertson, Sydney 1879</ref> Once in South Australia, William and Emily had a further ten children.\n\n==Family==\nWilliam married twice: to Sarah Roper (died 1833) on 1 November 1813, and to Emily McGeorge (c.1814 \u2013 5 August 1876) on 12 January 1835. In total he had 21 children and 78 grandchildren.<ref name=adb>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography |last= Tregenza |first= John |year= 1966 |id= A010409b |title=  Giles, William (1791\u20131862) |accessdate= 24 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=detail/>\n\n;Children with Sarah Roper\n* William Giles, (c. 1814 \u2013 14 January 1875)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article40092316 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=16 January 1875 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia |quote=Deaths. At his residence (in) Hackney, William Giles, aged 60.}}</ref> married Margaret McFarlane (11 June 1821 \u2013 22 October 1901), daughter of [[Allan McFarlane]];<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4913146 |title=The Late Mrs. W. Giles |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=23 October 1901 |accessdate=1 February 2013 |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> home at [[Hackney, South Australia|Hackney]] then George Street, [[Norwood, South Australia|Norwood]]. He later had a business in [[Kanmantoo, South Australia|Kanmantoo]] and was not involved in public affairs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article40082736 |title=The Late Mr. Wm. Giles |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XL |issue=8789 |location=South Australia |date=15 January 1875 |accessdate=4 April 2018 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Their son Alan McFarlane Giles ( \u2013 24 November 1888), stationmaster at Tennant Creek, was the sole survivor of a relief party sent to Attack Creek in 1883, saved by an [[Australian aborigine|aboriginal]] woman, and died of [[brain fever]] at [[Renner Springs, Northern Territory|Renner Springs]] five years later, following a murder to which he was a close witness.\n* Henry Giles (1816 \u2013 10 February 1888)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article46862625 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=13 February 1888 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia |quote=Deaths. At Braemar, Stirling West, Henry Giles, aged 72.}}</ref> married Jane Leslie (1825 \u2013 13 November 1892) in Scotland in 1845;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48558893 |title=Death of an Old Colonist |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=14 November 1892 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> home \"Braemar\", [[Aldgate, South Australia|Stirling West]]. Co-founded stock and station firm Giles & Smith.<ref name=clement/> Their eldest daughter, Amy, married [[John Fullerton Cleland#Family|George Fullerton Cleland]] in 1878.<ref>Lindsay Cleland, [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/cleland-george-fullerton-3232/text4873 'Cleland, George Fullerton (1852\u20131931)'], ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', National Centre of Biography, Australian National University, accessed 29 January 2013</ref>\n* Mary Giles (c. 1818 \u2013 19 September 1893)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article53623019 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=22 September 1893 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia |quote=Deaths. Mary, beloved wife of Josiah Partridge, of Malvern, near Clarendon, SA, aged 75. }}</ref> married Josiah Partridge (1805 \u2013 27 November 1897)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54518502 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=7 December 1897 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> on 22 June 1840;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27441558 |title=Markets |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=27 June 1840 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> home \"Malvern\", near [[Clarendon, South Australia|Clarendon]].\n* [[Thomas Giles (pastoralist)|Thomas \"Tom\" Giles]] (1820 \u2013 12 February 1899)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54410620 |title=The Late Mr. T. Giles |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=21 February 1899 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  married Mary O'Halloran (died c. 1 October 1915) on 20 January 1859. He developed pastoral leases on the Eyre and Yorke Peninsulas.\n:*Dr. W(illiam) Anstey Giles (c. 1860 \u2013 7 May 1944)<!--married Ruth (died 9 September 1907)-->\n:*T. O'Halloran Giles (1863 \u2013 ) married Jean Balfour St. Clair Barr Smith (20 December 1864 \u2013 ) on 4 October 1888. She was a daughter of [[Robert Barr Smith]].\n::*Hew O'Halloran Giles ( \u2013 ) married Nellie Cosford Verco (1901\u20131965), eldest daughter of Dr. W. A. Verco, and great-granddaughter of [[James Crabb Verco]], on 27 October 1920\n:::*[[Geoffrey O'Halloran Giles]] MLC, MHR (27 June 1923 \u2013 18 December 1990)\n::*Robert O'Halloran Giles (c. 1896 \u2013 9 April 1918) was killed in action in Italy.\n:*Dr. Henry O'Halloran Giles (c. 1867 \u2013 9 March 1911)\n:*Eustace Giles (1866 \u2013 24 December 1927), solicitor of Yarra House, Anderson-street, South Yarra, Victoria, died in London\n* James Giles (c. 1821 \u2013 20 December 1861)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article881234 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The South Australian Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=23 December 1861 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> married Eliza Dean (c. 1823 \u2013 5 April 1882) in 1848\n* Jane Isabella \"Minnie\" Giles (1824 \u2013 c. 19 August 1894)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article53648022 |title=Funeral of Mrs. Alfred Watts |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=22 August 1894 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}} This reference includes a useful list of mourners.</ref> married Alfred Watts (c. 1815 \u2013 28 November 1884)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article43803917 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=3 December 1884 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> on 18 May 1842<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article36248709 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[Launceston Examiner]] |location=Tas. |date=4 June 1842 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=5 Edition: Evening |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> They were the original owners of [[Leabrook, South Australia|Leabrook]].<ref>http://www.slsa.sa.gov.au/manning/pn/l/l2.htm Manning Index of South Australia \u2013 Placenames</ref> Watts was a fellow passenger on the ''Hartley'' with Giles and his family, as was Rev. [[T. Q. Stow]], who performed the service. \n* John Stokes Giles (1825\u2013)<ref name=detail/>\n* Lydia Giles (1827 \u2013 25 January 1910)<ref>{{cite news |title=Second Edition |url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=HC19100315.2.20 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |newspaper=Horowhenua Chronicle |date=15 March 1910 |page=3}}</ref> married [[George Waterhouse (politician)|George Waterhouse]] (6 April 1824 \u2013 6 August 1906) on 5 July 1848.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48729267 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=8 July 1848 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Waterhouse was Premier of South Australia from 1861 to 1863 and Premier of New Zealand from 1872 to 1873.\n:*One of their two adopted daughters married [[William Fitzherbert (mayor)|William Fitzherbert]] (1842 \u2013 2 February 1906) in 1876\n* Samuel (1830\u2013 )<ref name=detail/>\n* Sarah (1833\u2013 )\n\n;Children with Emily McGeorge\n* Emily Rebecca Giles (1836 \u2013 24 January 1929)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article35321699 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=25 January 1929 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=12 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> married [[Francis William Stokes]] (1832 \u2013 2 August 1889)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3499537 |title=Cable Messages |newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]] |date=5 August 1889 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> on 17 April 1861<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article50017602 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=20 April 1861 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> developed Konetta (Coonatto ?) Station.\n* George Hartley Giles (c. 1837 \u2013 ) was born on ship ''Hartley'' at sea;<ref name=detail/> practised law, admitted to Supreme Court in 1862,<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article40467328 Accessions to the Bar], SA Register, 24 March 1862, p.2</ref> but was struck off the rolls for misappropriation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41018297 |title=Law and Criminal Courts. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=13 December 1865 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He moved to Queensland, where he ran foul of the law several times. Later references are elusive \u2013 perhaps like [[Charles Whitmore Babbage]], the family used its considerable influence to help him start over in another place, perhaps under another name.\n* Edward Hollingworth Giles (1838 \u2013 18 July 1839)\n* Percy Ludlow Giles (1839 \u2013 20 December 1840)\n* Leonard Hollway Giles (18 May 1841 \u2013 15 January 1898)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article87771096 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The Chronicle (Adelaide)|The Chronicle]] |location=Adelaide |date=22 January 1898 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=9 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> married Marianne <!--not Marrianne, Marion--> Baily (13 February 1854 \u2013 5 May 1901)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article56083783 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=11 May 1901 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> on 12 September 1878<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42995531 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=19 September 1878 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* Hubert Giles (21 October 1842 \u2013 11 August 1901<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4851397 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=12 August 1901 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>), prizewinning student at Adelaide Educational Institution, married Charlotte Julian Kingston (11 September 1845 \u2013 20 May 1913), youngest daughter of Sir [[George Strickland Kingston]] on 17 March 1880.\n* [[Clement Giles]] (1844 \u2013 28 July 1926),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54861976 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=28 July 1926 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=10 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> pastoralist, merchant and politician. A prizewinning student at [[Adelaide Educational Institution]], he became Secretary-manager and first London representative of the South Australian Farmers' Co-operative Union, and later, sole elected representative of Australian farmers on the compulsory wheat pool of 1917.<ref name=adb/><ref name=clement>Carl Bridge (1983) [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/giles-clement-6380 Giles, Clement (1844\u20131926)], ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Vol 9</ref> He married Isabel Cockburn (sister of [[John Cockburn (Australian politician)|Sir John Cockburn]]) on 7 August 1872<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39267743 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=9 August 1872 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* Louis Henry Lobeck Giles (14 July 1845 \u2013 21 November 1902) married Alice Margaret \"Alison\" Andrews (9 February 1862 \u2013 ), second daughter of [[William Buckton Andrews|Rev. Canon Andrews]], on 26 November 1884. He was a prizewinning student at [[Adelaide Educational Institution]] then a licensed land broker at the [[Grange, South Australia|Grange]] and Adelaide.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4900017 |title=Personal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=22 November 1902 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* Acland Giles (c. January 1847 \u2013 8 June 1858)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49777035 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=9 June 1858 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}This reference reckons him the twelfth son.</ref> A student at Adelaide Educational Institution, he won prizes in 1856 and 1857, the second posthumously.\n* Mortimer Giles (1848 \u2013 17 May 1914)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article6416614 |title=Personal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=18 May 1914 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=14 |publisher=National Library of Australia}} A comprehensive obituary.</ref> married Agnes Reid Andrews (c. 1849 \u2013 18 July 1907), the daughter of [[Richard Bullock Andrews|Mr. Justice Andrews]], on 16 May 1874.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39821841 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=19 May 1874 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}} An instance of brothers marrying cousins.</ref> He was a prizewinning student at J. L. Young's [[Adelaide Educational Institution]]. In 1904 he was appointed Registrar-General of Deeds, Registrar of Building Societies, Commissioner of Trade Marks, and Registrar of Copyrights.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4983283 |title=The Civil Service |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=30 June 1904 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n:*Mortimer Giles (1887\u20131979) was admitted to the Bar in 1912.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59233322 |title=Admitted to the Bar |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=22 July 1912 |accessdate=29 January 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* Caroline Ada Giles (28 February 1850 \u2013 21 May 1933)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41487200 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=23 May 1933 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> married Charles Edward Stokes (1851\u20131911) on 12 June 1877.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article33749718 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The South Australian Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=13 June 1877 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> She had some success as an artist.<ref>[http://www.daao.org.au/bio/caroline-giles/#artist_biography Biography \u2013 Caroline Giles] ''Design & Art Australia Online'' www.daao.org.au</ref>\n* Florence Giles (13 January 1852 \u2013 30 January 1930)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54160183 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The Register News-Pictorial]] |location=Adelaide |date=31 January 1930 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> married Rev. Francis Herbert Stokes (29 December 1854 \u2013 21 February 1929)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article87455057 |title=Obituary. |newspaper=[[The Chronicle (Adelaide)|The Chronicle]] |location=Adelaide |date=2 March 1929 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=47 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> on 3 September 1879<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article29374537 |title=Family Notices. |newspaper=[[The South Australian Advertiser]] |location=Adelaide |date=4 September 1879 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=4 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n:*Francis Herbert Stokes, jr. (c. 1890 \u2013 27 April 1915) was killed at [[Gallipoli]] in 1915.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59602439 |title=PTE. F. H. Stokes |newspaper=[[South Australian Register|The Register (Adelaide, SA : 1901 - 1929)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=22 June 1915 |accessdate=28 January 2013 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n;Summary\n<center>\n{| class=wikitable\n!   ||         || born ||boy||girl|| died || Age at death\n|-\n| 1 || William || 1814 || 1 ||    || 1875 || 61\n|-\n| 2 || Henry   || 1816 || 2 ||    || 1888 || 72\n|-\n| 3 || Mary    || 1818 ||   || 1  || 1893 || 75\n|-\n| 4 || Thomas  || 1820 || 3 ||    || 1899 || 79\n|-\n| 5 || James   || 1821 || 4 ||    || 1861 || 40\n|-\n| 6 || Jane    || 1824 ||   || 2  || 1894 || 70\n|-\n| 7 || John    || 1825 || 5 ||    ||  ?   ||  \n|-\n| 8 || Lydia   || 1827 ||   || 3  || 1910 || 83\n|-\n| 9 || Samuel  || 1830 || 6 ||    ||  ?   ||  \n|-\n|   || Sarah   || 1833 ||   ||    ||  ?   || Died at birth?\n|- align=center\n|colspan=7| Mrs Sarah Giles died 1833\n|-\n|10 || Emily   || 1836 ||   || 4 || 1929 || 93\n|-\n|11 || George  || 1837 || 7 ||   ||  ?   ||\n|-\n|12 || Edward  || 1838 || 8 ||   || 1839 || 1\n|-\n|13 || Percy   || 1839 || 9 ||   || 1840 || 1\n|-\n|14 || Leonard || 1841 ||10 ||   || 1898 || 57 \n|-\n|15 || Hubert  || 1842 ||11 ||   || 1901 || 59\n|-\n|16 || Clement || 1844 ||12 ||   || 1926 || 82\n|-\n|17 || Louis   || 1845 ||13 ||   || 1902 || 57\n|-\n|18 || Acland  || 1847 ||14 ||   || 1858 || 11 \n|-\n|19 || Mortimer|| 1848 ||15 ||   || 1914 || 66    \n|-\n|20 || Caroline|| 1850 ||   || 5 || 1933 || 83 \n|-\n|21 || Florence|| 1852 ||   || 6 || 1930 || 78   \n|}\n</center>\n\n==Business life==\nShortly after arrival on Kangaroo Island, Giles, [[Thomas Hudson Beare (pioneer)|T. H. Beare]], and [[Henry Mildred]] imported a batch of [[Merino]] ewes from [[Tasmania|Van Diemens Land]] to [[Kangaroo Island]], some of the first brought into the colony, though stock losses on the unusually long trip aboard the ''Cygnet'' were considerable.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article160093755 |title=The Merino in South Australia |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |volume=XLI |issue=2213 |location=South Australia |date=1 March 1884 |accessdate=13 January 2017 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nGiles was appointed Stipendiary Magistrate by [[John Hindmarsh|Governor Hindmarsh]] in 1838<ref name=Heaton/> then appointed as the third colonial manager of the [[South Australian Company]] in January 1841, succeeding [[David McLaren (Colonial Manager)|David McLaren]].<ref name=adb/> He continued as manager until 1861, when he retired.\n\n==Political life==\nGiles stood for the [[Electoral district of Port Adelaide]] in the [[South Australian Legislative Council|first elected parliament]] in July 1851, but was narrowly defeated by [[George Hall (Australian politician)|Captain George Hall]].<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39184005/3952567 Death of the Hon. George Hall, MLC] ''South Australian Register'' 29 January 1867 p.3 accessed 26 June 2011</ref><!--can he have both been beaten at Port Adelaide and won Yatala in 1851?-->\nHe was elected as member for the District of Yatala for five sessions of the [[South Australian Legislative Council]], from July 1851 until 1854.<ref>[http://www.parliament.sa.gov.au/AboutParliament/From1836/Documents/StatisticalRecordoftheLegislature1836to20093.pdf Statistical Record of the Legislature 1836\u20132007] ''Parliament of South Australia'' parliament.sa.gov.au. Tabled 24 April 2007, accessed 16 September 2011.</ref> He was a devout [[Congregationalist]]. As a legislator he opposed state aid to religion,<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/earlyhistorysou00blacgoog |title=The Early History of South Australia: A Romantic Experiment in Colonization |author=John Blacket |year=1907 |publisher=Methodist Book Depot}}</ref> as did his close friend, Rev. [[Thomas Stow|T. Q. Stow]].<ref name=Heaton/>\n\nHe died at his home in [[Beaumont, South Australia|Beaumont]] on 11 May 1862.<ref name=adb/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Giles, William}}\n[[Category:1791 births]]\n[[Category:1862 deaths]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Great Staughton]]\n[[Category:Settlers of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the South Australian Legislative Council]]\n[[Category:People educated at Kimbolton School]]\n[[Category:South Australian Company Colonial Managers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:South Australian families]]\n", "name_user": "Cowdy001", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Giles_(colonial_manager)"}
