430\u043d\u043e-\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a] <sup>(Ukrainian)</sup>\n|footnotes =\n}}\n'''Hody-Dobrovidka''' ({{lang-uk|\u0413\u043e\u0301\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0301\u0434\u043a\u0430}}) is a village in [[Kolomyia Raion]] of [[Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast]] in [[Western Ukraine]]. The population of the village is around 967 inhabitants, and local government is administered by Hodo-Dobrovidska village council.<ref>[http://rada.info/rada/04356774/ \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0456\u043b\u044c\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430] {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe village is in a flat terrain on the altitude of {{convert|335|m|foot}} above sea level and area of the village totals is {{cvt|12.88|sqkm}}. It is at a distance {{convert|9|km|mi}} from the district center [[Kolomyia]] and {{convert|65|km|mi}} from the regional center of [[Ivano-Frankivsk]].\n\n== History and Attractions ==\nThe village was established in 1939 from the two separate villages, Hody and Dobrovidka.<ref>[[:uk:\u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0430|Hody-Dobrovidka]]</ref> The first written record about Dobrovidka dates back to 1451, and Gody village mentioned in 1857.<ref>[http://drymba.net/uk/1024960-selo-hody-dobrovidka \u0421\u0435\u043b\u043e \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0430: \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0432\u0443\u043b\u0438\u0446\u044c] {{in lang|uk}}</ref> The village has an architectural monument of local importance of Ivano-Frankivsk region. It is the Church of St. Dmitry 1923 (Wooden).<ref>[http://decerkva.org.ua/fra/hody-dobrovidka_dmytra.html \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u0432. \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0430 1923] {{in lang|uk}}</ref> The church belongs to the architectural monuments of local importance.<ref>[http://ukrainaincognita.com/ivano-frankivska-oblast/pamyatky-arkhitektury-mistsevogo-znachennya-ivano-frankivska-oblast-chastyn-0 \u041f\u0430\u043c'\u044f\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u0430\u0440\u0445\u0456\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0438 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u0446\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f. \u0406\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e-\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c. / \u0427\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 3 / 915, \u0426\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u0432. \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0456\u044f (\u0434\u0435\u0440.) 1852 \u0440. (N 801)] {{in lang|uk}}</ref> There is also the Church of St. George 1926 (Wooden).<ref>[http://decerkva.org.ua/fra/hody-dobrovidka_yuria.html \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0430. \u0426\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u0432. \u042e\u0440\u0456\u044f 1926] {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n\n== Famous people ==\n* '''Melnychuk Petro Dmytrovych'''<ref>\n*[http://ntsh.org/content/ganitkevich-yaroslav-ukrayinskiy-medichniy-kalendar-na-2013-rik \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440 \u043d\u0430 2013 \u0440\u0456\u043a/1913, 14 \u043b\u0438\u043f\u043d\u044f \u2013 100 \u0440\u043e\u043a\u0456\u0432] {{in lang|uk}}\n*http://mistaua.com/\u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0456/\u0412\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0456/\u043c\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0443\u043a-\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e-\u0434\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447/1551/?setcity=2304 {{in lang|uk}}</ref> (1913-2004) &ndash; Candidate of Pharmaceutical Sciences, Associate Professor, Deputy Director for Science of Lviv State Medical Institute (1944-1961), known phytotherapeutist. He graduated from the [[Lviv University]] (1939), was twice sentenced to death, once by the [[Soviet annexation of Eastern Galicia, Volhynia and Northern Bukovina|Bolsheviks]] (1941) and once by the [[German-occupied Europe |German occupiers]] (1944).\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://atu.minregion.gov.ua/en/ustriy_page/5098 Hodo-Dobrovidska village council]\n* [http://weather.in.ua/en/ivano-frankovskaja/5324 weather.in.ua/Hody-Dobrovidka]\n\n{{Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast]]\n\n{{IvanoFrankivsk-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name = Hody-Dobrovidka\n|native_name = \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0430\n|image_skyline = File:\u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0430, \u0446\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0430.jpg\n|imagesize =\n|image_caption = The wooden church of St. George 1926\n|image_flag =\n|image_shield =\n|nickname =\n|motto =\n|image_map = \n|mapsize =\n|map_caption =\n|subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name ={{UKR}}\n|subdivision_type1 = [[Oblasts of Ukraine|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1 ={{flag|Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast}}\n|subdivision_type2 = [[Raions of Ukraine|District]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[File:Flag of Kolomyisky raion in Ivano-Frankivsk oblast.png|size|25px]] [[Kolomyia Raion]]\n|established_title =\n|established_date =\n|established_title1 =\n|established_date1 =\n|leader_title =\n|leader_name =\n|area_magnitude =\n|area_total_km2 = 12,88\n|area_water_km2 =\n|population_as_of =\n|population_note =\n|population_total = 967\n|population_metro =\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n|pushpin_map            = Ukraine Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast\n|pushpin_label_position =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Ukraine Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|coordinates      = {{coord|48|36|08|N|25|04|20|E|region:UA|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m = 335\n| timezone = EET\n| utc_offset = +2\n| timezone_DST = EEST\n| utc_offset_DST = +3\n| postal_code_type = [[Postal code]]\n|postal_code = 78244\n| area_code_type = [[Telephone numbering plan|Area code]]\n| area_code = +380 3433\n|blank_info =\n|blank1_info =\n|website = [http://1ua.com.ua/c22274  \u0441\u0435\u043b\u043e \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0430 / \u0440\u0430\u0439\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u041a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043c\u0438\u044f / \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u0406\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e-\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a] <sup>(Ukrainian)</sup>\n|footnotes =\n}}\n'''Hody-Dobrovidka''' ({{lang-uk|\u0413\u043e\u0301\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0301\u0434\u043a\u0430}}) is a village in [[Kolomyia Raion]] of [[Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast]] in [[Western Ukraine]]. The population of the village is around 967 inhabitants, and local government is administered by Hodo-Dobrovidska village council.<ref>[http://rada.info/rada/04356774/ \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0456\u043b\u044c\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430] {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe village is in a flat terrain on the altitude of {{convert|335|m|foot}} above sea level and area of the village totals is {{cvt|12.88|sqkm}}. It is at a distance {{convert|9|km|mi}} from the district center [[Kolomyia]] and {{convert|65|km|mi}} from the regional center of [[Ivano-Frankivsk]].\n\n== History and Attractions ==\nThe village was established in 1939 from the two separate villages, Hody and Dobrovidka.<ref>[[:uk:\u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0430|Hody-Dobrovidka]]</ref> The first written record about Dobrovidka dates back to 1451, and Gody village mentioned in 1857.<ref>[http://drymba.net/uk/1024960-selo-hody-dobrovidka \u0421\u0435\u043b\u043e \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0430: \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0432\u0443\u043b\u0438\u0446\u044c] {{in lang|uk}}</ref> The village has an architectural monument of local importance of Ivano-Frankivsk region. It is the Church of St. Dmitry 1923 (Wooden).<ref>[http://decerkva.org.ua/fra/hody-dobrovidka_dmytra.html \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u0432. \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0430 1923] {{in lang|uk}}</ref> The church belongs to the architectural monuments of local importance.<ref>[http://ukrainaincognita.com/ivano-frankivska-oblast/pamyatky-arkhitektury-mistsevogo-znachennya-ivano-frankivska-oblast-chastyn-0 \u041f\u0430\u043c'\u044f\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u0430\u0440\u0445\u0456\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0438 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u0446\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f. \u0406\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e-\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c. / \u0427\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 3 / 915, \u0426\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u0432. \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0456\u044f (\u0434\u0435\u0440.) 1852 \u0440. (N 801)] {{in lang|uk}}</ref> There are also the Church of St. George 1926 (Wooden).<ref>[http://decerkva.org.ua/fra/hody-dobrovidka_yuria.html \u0413\u043e\u0434\u0438-\u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043a\u0430. \u0426\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u0432. \u042e\u0440\u0456\u044f 1926] {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n\n== Famous people ==\n* '''Melnychuk Petro Dmytrovych'''<ref>\n*[http://ntsh.org/content/ganitkevich-yaroslav-ukrayinskiy-medichniy-kalendar-na-2013-rik \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440 \u043d\u0430 2013 \u0440\u0456\u043a/1913, 14 \u043b\u0438\u043f\u043d\u044f \u2013 100 \u0440\u043e\u043a\u0456\u0432] {{in lang|uk}}\n*http://mistaua.com/\u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0456/\u0412\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0456/\u043c\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0443\u043a-\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e-\u0434\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447/1551/?setcity=2304 {{in lang|uk}}</ref> (1913-2004) &ndash; Candidate of Pharmaceutical Sciences, Associate Professor, Deputy Director for Science of Lviv State Medical Institute (1944-1961), known phytotherapeutist. He graduated from the [[Lviv University]] (1939), was twice sentenced to death, once by the [[Soviet annexation of Eastern Galicia, Volhynia and Northern Bukovina|Bolsheviks]] (1941) and once by the [[German-occupied Europe |German occupiers]] (1944).\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://atu.minregion.gov.ua/en/ustriy_page/5098 Hodo-Dobrovidska village council]\n* [http://weather.in.ua/en/ivano-frankovskaja/5324 weather.in.ua/Hody-Dobrovidka]\n\n{{Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Ivano-Frankivsk Oblast]]\n\n{{IvanoFrankivsk-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Funtoedit1212", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correlation of predicate and subject", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hody-Dobrovidka"}
{"title_page": "Arlene Stringer-Cuevas", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Arlene Stringer-Cuevas\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| office              = Member of the [[New York City Council]] from [[Washington Heights]]\n| term_start          = 1976\n| term_end            = 1977\n| predecessor         = \n| successor           = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1933|9|25}}\n| birth_place         = [[The Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2020|4|3|1933|9|25}}\n| death_place         = [[The Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| spouse              = Ronald Stringer, Carlos Cuevas\n| children            = [[Scott Stringer]]\n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n| alma_mater          = \n| otherparty          = \n| education           = \n| occupation          = \n| website             = \n| birth_name          = Arlene Gluss\n| relatives           = [[Bella Abzug]] (cousin)\n}}\n\n'''Arlene Stringer-Cuevas''' ([[Birth name|n\u00e9e]] '''Gluss'''; September 25, 1933 &ndash; April 3, 2020) was an American politician, educator, and civil servant. She was a schoolteacher before serving on the [[New York City Council]] from 1976 to 1977. Stringer-Cuevas later worked for the [[New York City Human Resources Administration]] for 16 years until her retirement in 1994. She died during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] due to complications brought on by [[COVID-19]].\n\n==Early life==\nStringer-Cuevas was born Arlene Gluss in the [[Bronx]] in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and was a school teacher. She lived in the [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] neighborhood of Manhattan. She was Jewish.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thejewishvoice.com/2013/08/nyc-comptroller-candidate-scott-stringer-enjoys-celebrity-support/|title=NYC Comptroller Candidate Scott Stringer Enjoys Celebrity Support|date=August 21, 2013|website=The Jewish Voice|language=en-US|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nStringer-Cuevas served as her neighborhood's Democratic Party district leader from 1969 to 1976.<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = April 5, 2020| date= September 12, 1976 | title= 4-Way Democratic Council Battle Stirring Interest in Sixth District | first= Glenn | last= Fowler | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1976/09/12/79320550.html }}</ref> She was elected to the [[New York City Council]] in 1976 after winning a four-person primary for the Democratic nomination<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = April 5, 2020| date= September 15, 1976 | title= Mrs. Stringer Beats 3 Rivals In a Manhattan Council Race|url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1976/09/15/80516160.html }}</ref>, becoming the first woman to represent [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]]. Stringer-Cuevas was defeated in the Democratic primary in 1977.<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = April 5, 2020| date= November 9, 1977 |first= Glenn | last= Fowler | title= Council Gets New Look: More Women and Minorities |url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1977/11/09/75699575.html }}</ref>\n\nStringer-Cuevas then worked for the [[New York City Human Resources Administration]] from 1978 until her retirement in 1994.<ref name=nyp/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nStringer-Cuevas was part of a politically active family. Her first husband, Ronald Stringer, was an assistant to New York City Mayor [[Abraham Beame]].<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = April 5, 2020| date= July 1, 1976| title= West Side Democrats Are Again Ensnarled in Political Wars Over Nominations |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/01/archives/west-side-democrats-are-again-ensnarled-in-political-wars-over.html | first = Frank | last = Lynn }}</ref> Her second husband, Carlos Cuevas, was the New York City Clerk and a Deputy Borough President of the Bronx.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.cityandstateny.com/articles/personality/interviews-profiles/scott-stringer-millennial-mayor.html | title= Scott Stringer, millennial for mayor |access-date = April 5, 2020 | date= July 15, 2019 | first =Jeff | last= Coltin | work= City and State NY}}</ref> Stringer-Cuevas' son [[Scott Stringer]] was elected [[Borough President]] of Manhattan and [[New York City Comptroller]]. She was the cousin of politician women's rights pioneer [[Bella Abzug]].<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = April 5, 2020| date= October 2, 1972| title= Mrs. Abzug Wins Party Approval to Succeed Ryan|url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1972/10/02/79430726.html }}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, 2020, at the age of 86, Stringer-Cuevas died from complications due to [[COVID-19]] at [[Montefiore Medical Center]] in the Bronx.<ref name=nyp>{{cite news|last=Calder|first=Rich|url=https://www.nypost.com/2020/04/03/comptroller-scott-stringers-mother-arlene-has-died-from-coronavirus/|title=Comptroller Scott Stringer's mom dead from coronavirus|date=April 3, 2020|work=New York Post|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[http://oralhistory.nypl.org/interviews/arlene-stringer-cuevas-zydu7m 2015 interview] by the [[New York Public Library]] Community Oral History Project - {{int:Wm-license-cc-zero-text}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Striger-Cuevas, Arlene}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:People from Washington Heights, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Council members]]\n[[Category:Women city councillors in the United States]]\n[[Category:Women in New York (state) politics]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Educators from New York City]]\n[[Category:20th-century United States government officials]]\n[[Category:American women civil servants]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:American women educators]]\n[[Category:Jewish American people in New York (state) politics]]\n[[Category:Jewish women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Arlene Stringer-Cuevas\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| office              = Member of the [[New York City Council]] from [[Washington Heights]]\n| term_start          = 1976\n| term_end            = 1977\n| predecessor         = \n| successor           = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1933|9|25}}\n| birth_place         = [[The Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2020|4|3|1933|9|25}}\n| death_place         = [[The Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| spouse              = Ronald Stringer, Carlos Cuevas\n| children            = [[Scott Stringer]]\n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n| alma_mater          = \n| otherparty          = \n| education           = \n| occupation          = \n| website             = \n| birth_name          = Arlene Gluss\n| relatives           = [[Bella Abzug]] (cousin)\n}}\n\n'''Arlene Stringer-Cuevas''' ([[Birth name|n\u00e9e]] '''Gluss'''; September 25, 1933 &ndash; April 3, 2020) was an American politician, educator, and civil servant. She was a schoolteacher before serving on the [[New York City Council]] from 1976 to 1977. Stringer-Cuevas later worked for the [[New York City Human Resources Administration]] for 16 years until her retirement in 1994. She died during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] due to complications brought on by [[COVID-19]].\n\n==Early life==\nStringer-Cuevas was born Arlene Gluss in the [[Bronx]] in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and was a school teacher. She lived in the [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] neighborhood of Manhattan. She was Jewish.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thejewishvoice.com/2013/08/nyc-comptroller-candidate-scott-stringer-enjoys-celebrity-support/|title=NYC Comptroller Candidate Scott Stringer Enjoys Celebrity Support|date=August 21, 2013|website=The Jewish Voice|language=en-US|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nStringer-Cuevas served as her neighborhood's Democratic Party district leader from 1969 to 1976.<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = April 5, 2020| date= September 12, 1976 | title= 4-Way Democratic Council Battle Stirring Interest in Sixth District | first= Glenn | last= Fowler | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1976/09/12/79320550.html }}</ref> She was elected to the [[New York City Council]] in 1976 after winning a four-person primary for the Democratic nomination<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = April 5, 2020| date= September 15, 1976 | title= Mrs. Stringer Beats 3 Rivals In a Manhattan Council Race|url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1976/09/15/80516160.html }}</ref>, becoming the first woman to represent [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]]. Stringer-Cuevas was defeated in the Democratic primary in 1977.<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = April 5, 2020| date= November 9, 1977 |first= Glenn | last= Fowler | title= Council Gets New Look: More Women and Minorities |url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1977/11/09/75699575.html }}</ref>\n\nStringer-Cuevas then worked for the [[New York City Human Resources Administration]] from 1978 until her retirement in 1994.<ref name=nyp/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nStringer-Cuevas was part of a politically active family. Her first husband, Ronald Stringer, was an assistant to New York City Mayor [[Abraham Beame]].<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = April 5, 2020| date= July 1, 1976| title= West Side Democrats Are Again Ensnarled in Political Wars Over Nominations |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/01/archives/west-side-democrats-are-again-ensnarled-in-political-wars-over.html | first = Frank | last = Lynn }}</ref> Her second husband, Carlos Cuevas, was the New York City Clerk and a Deputy Borough President of the Bronx.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.cityandstateny.com/articles/personality/interviews-profiles/scott-stringer-millennial-mayor.html | title= Scott Stringer, millennial for mayor |access-date = April 5, 2020 | date= July 15, 2019 | first =Jeff | last= Coltin | work= City and State NY}}</ref> Stringer-Cuevas' son [[Scott Stringer]] was elected [[Borough President]] of Manhattan and [[New York City Comptroller]]. She was the cousin of politician women's right pioneer [[Bella Abzug]].<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = April 5, 2020| date= October 2, 1972| title= Mrs. Abzug Wins Party Approval to Succeed Ryan|url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1972/10/02/79430726.html }}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, 2020, at the age of 86, Stringer-Cuevas died from complications due to [[COVID-19]] at [[Montefiore Medical Center]] in the Bronx.<ref name=nyp>{{cite news|last=Calder|first=Rich|url=https://www.nypost.com/2020/04/03/comptroller-scott-stringers-mother-arlene-has-died-from-coronavirus/|title=Comptroller Scott Stringer's mom dead from coronavirus|date=April 3, 2020|work=New York Post|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[http://oralhistory.nypl.org/interviews/arlene-stringer-cuevas-zydu7m 2015 interview] by the [[New York Public Library]] Community Oral History Project - {{int:Wm-license-cc-zero-text}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Striger-Cuevas, Arlene}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:People from Washington Heights, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Council members]]\n[[Category:Women city councillors in the United States]]\n[[Category:Women in New York (state) politics]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Educators from New York City]]\n[[Category:20th-century United States government officials]]\n[[Category:American women civil servants]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:American women educators]]\n[[Category:Jewish American people in New York (state) politics]]\n[[Category:Jewish women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Wwwhatsup", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:typo?", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arlene_Stringer-Cuevas"}
